# BullMQ: Jobs, Workers, Queues, and Scheduling

## Introduction

BullMQ is the premier job queue library for Node.js, built on top of Redis. It enables you to offload time-consuming tasks — sending emails, processing images, generating reports — from your request handlers into background workers. This pattern is essential for building responsive, scalable backend systems.

## Why Message Queues?

```
Without Queue (Synchronous):
User ──> API ──> Send Email (3s) ──> Generate PDF (5s) ──> Response (8s total)

With Queue (Asynchronous):
User ──> API ──> Enqueue Jobs ──> Response (50ms)
                      │
                      ▼
              Background Workers:
              Worker 1: Send Email (3s)
              Worker 2: Generate PDF (5s)
```

## BullMQ Architecture

```
┌──────────┐     ┌───────────┐     ┌──────────────┐
│ Producer │────>│   Redis   │────>│   Worker(s)  │
│ (API)    │     │  (Queue)  │     │  (Consumers) │
└──────────┘     └───────────┘     └──────────────┘
     │                                    │
     │  add job to queue                  │  process jobs
     │                                    │
     ▼                                    ▼
  Job States: waiting ──> active ──> completed
                                 └──> failed ──> waiting (retry)
```

## Setup

```javascript
import { Queue, Worker, QueueScheduler, QueueEvents } from 'bullmq';
import Redis from 'ioredis';

// Shared Redis connection config
const connection = {
  host: process.env.REDIS_HOST || 'localhost',
  port: parseInt(process.env.REDIS_PORT) || 6379,
  maxRetriesPerRequest: null, // Required for BullMQ
};

// Create a queue
const emailQueue = new Queue('email', { connection });
const pdfQueue = new Queue('pdf-generation', { connection });
```

## Adding Jobs (Producer)

```javascript
// Simple job
await emailQueue.add('welcome-email', {
  to: 'user@example.com',
  subject: 'Welcome!',
  template: 'welcome',
  data: { name: 'Alice' },
});

// Job with options
await emailQueue.add('order-confirmation', {
  to: 'user@example.com',
  orderId: 'ORD-123',
}, {
  priority: 1,                    // Lower = higher priority
  delay: 5000,                    // Delay 5 seconds before processing
  attempts: 3,                    // Retry up to 3 times
  backoff: {
    type: 'exponential',          // exponential or fixed
    delay: 1000,                  // Initial delay: 1s, then 2s, 4s
  },
  removeOnComplete: {
    age: 3600,                    // Keep completed jobs for 1 hour
    count: 1000,                  // Keep last 1000 completed jobs
  },
  removeOnFail: {
    age: 86400,                   // Keep failed jobs for 24 hours
  },
});

// Bulk add
await emailQueue.addBulk([
  { name: 'digest', data: { userId: 1 }, opts: { priority: 5 } },
  { name: 'digest', data: { userId: 2 }, opts: { priority: 5 } },
  { name: 'digest', data: { userId: 3 }, opts: { priority: 5 } },
]);
```

### From Express Route

```javascript
import express from 'express';
const app = express();

app.post('/api/orders', authenticate, async (req, res) => {
  // Create order in DB (fast)
  const order = await prisma.order.create({
    data: { ...req.body, userId: req.user.id },
  });

  // Offload slow tasks to queues
  await Promise.all([
    emailQueue.add('order-confirmation', {
      orderId: order.id,
      userId: req.user.id,
    }),
    pdfQueue.add('invoice', {
      orderId: order.id,
    }),
    emailQueue.add('notify-warehouse', {
      orderId: order.id,
      items: order.items,
    }, { delay: 60000 }), // Wait 1 min (allow cancellation window)
  ]);

  // Respond immediately
  res.status(201).json({ order, message: 'Order placed successfully' });
});
```

## Processing Jobs (Worker)

```javascript
// worker.js - Run as a separate process
import { Worker } from 'bullmq';

const emailWorker = new Worker('email', async (job) => {
  console.log(`Processing job ${job.id}: ${job.name}`);

  switch (job.name) {
    case 'welcome-email':
      await sendWelcomeEmail(job.data);
      break;
    case 'order-confirmation':
      await sendOrderConfirmation(job.data);
      break;
    case 'notify-warehouse':
      await notifyWarehouse(job.data);
      break;
    default:
      throw new Error(`Unknown job name: ${job.name}`);
  }

  // Return value stored in job.returnvalue
  return { sent: true, timestamp: new Date().toISOString() };
}, {
  connection,
  concurrency: 5,           // Process 5 jobs simultaneously
  limiter: {
    max: 100,                // Max 100 jobs
    duration: 60000,         // Per 60 seconds (rate limiting)
  },
});

// Event handlers
emailWorker.on('completed', (job, result) => {
  console.log(`Job ${job.id} completed:`, result);
});

emailWorker.on('failed', (job, err) => {
  console.error(`Job ${job.id} failed:`, err.message);
  // Alert if final retry
  if (job.attemptsMade >= job.opts.attempts) {
    alertOps(`Email job permanently failed: ${job.id}`);
  }
});

emailWorker.on('error', (err) => {
  console.error('Worker error:', err);
});
```

## Job Progress and Events

```javascript
// Worker reporting progress
const pdfWorker = new Worker('pdf-generation', async (job) => {
  const { orderId } = job.data;

  await job.updateProgress(10);
  const orderData = await fetchOrderData(orderId);

  await job.updateProgress(30);
  const html = await renderTemplate(orderData);

  await job.updateProgress(60);
  const pdf = await generatePDF(html);

  await job.updateProgress(90);
  const url = await uploadToS3(pdf);

  await job.updateProgress(100);
  return { pdfUrl: url };
}, { connection });

// Monitoring with QueueEvents
const queueEvents = new QueueEvents('pdf-generation', { connection });

queueEvents.on('progress', ({ jobId, data }) => {
  console.log(`Job ${jobId} progress: ${data}%`);
});

queueEvents.on('completed', ({ jobId, returnvalue }) => {
  console.log(`Job ${jobId} completed:`, returnvalue);
});

queueEvents.on('failed', ({ jobId, failedReason }) => {
  console.error(`Job ${jobId} failed:`, failedReason);
});

// API endpoint to check job status
app.get('/api/jobs/:jobId', async (req, res) => {
  const job = await pdfQueue.getJob(req.params.jobId);
  if (!job) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Job not found' });

  const state = await job.getState();
  res.json({
    id: job.id,
    name: job.name,
    state,
    progress: job.progress,
    result: job.returnvalue,
    failedReason: job.failedReason,
    attemptsMade: job.attemptsMade,
    timestamp: job.timestamp,
  });
});
```

## Job Flows (Parent-Child)

```javascript
import { FlowProducer } from 'bullmq';

const flowProducer = new FlowProducer({ connection });

// Create a job flow: parent waits for all children
const flow = await flowProducer.add({
  name: 'process-order',
  queueName: 'orders',
  data: { orderId: 'ORD-123' },
  children: [
    {
      name: 'validate-payment',
      queueName: 'payments',
      data: { orderId: 'ORD-123', amount: 99.99 },
    },
    {
      name: 'check-inventory',
      queueName: 'inventory',
      data: { orderId: 'ORD-123', items: ['PROD-1', 'PROD-2'] },
    },
    {
      name: 'generate-invoice',
      queueName: 'pdf-generation',
      data: { orderId: 'ORD-123' },
    },
  ],
});

// Parent job only runs after ALL children complete
const orderWorker = new Worker('orders', async (job) => {
  // Access children results
  const childrenValues = await job.getChildrenValues();
  console.log('All children completed:', childrenValues);

  // Finalize order processing
  await prisma.order.update({
    where: { id: job.data.orderId },
    data: { status: 'PROCESSED' },
  });
}, { connection });
```

## Queue Dashboard (Bull Board)

```javascript
import { createBullBoard } from '@bull-board/api';
import { BullMQAdapter } from '@bull-board/api/bullMQAdapter';
import { ExpressAdapter } from '@bull-board/express';

const serverAdapter = new ExpressAdapter();
serverAdapter.setBasePath('/admin/queues');

createBullBoard({
  queues: [
    new BullMQAdapter(emailQueue),
    new BullMQAdapter(pdfQueue),
  ],
  serverAdapter,
});

app.use('/admin/queues', serverAdapter.getRouter());
// Visit http://localhost:3000/admin/queues for the dashboard
```

## NestJS Integration

```javascript
// queue.module.ts
import { BullModule } from '@nestjs/bullmq';

@Module({
  imports: [
    BullModule.forRoot({
      connection: {
        host: 'localhost',
        port: 6379,
      },
    }),
    BullModule.registerQueue({ name: 'email' }),
  ],
  providers: [EmailProcessor],
  exports: [BullModule],
})
export class QueueModule {}

// email.processor.ts
import { Processor, WorkerHost } from '@nestjs/bullmq';
import { Job } from 'bullmq';

@Processor('email')
export class EmailProcessor extends WorkerHost {
  async process(job: Job) {
    switch (job.name) {
      case 'welcome':
        return this.sendWelcome(job.data);
      case 'reset-password':
        return this.sendPasswordReset(job.data);
    }
  }
}

// order.service.ts
import { InjectQueue } from '@nestjs/bullmq';
import { Queue } from 'bullmq';

@Injectable()
export class OrderService {
  constructor(@InjectQueue('email') private emailQueue: Queue) {}

  async createOrder(data) {
    const order = await this.prisma.order.create({ data });
    await this.emailQueue.add('order-confirmation', { orderId: order.id });
    return order;
  }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Not handling worker crashes**: Use `autorun: true` (default) and handle the `error` event. BullMQ automatically re-adds active jobs that crash.
2. **Forgetting removeOnComplete**: Without it, Redis memory grows unbounded with completed job data.
3. **Running workers in the API process**: Workers should be separate processes so CPU-heavy jobs don't block request handling.
4. **Not setting maxRetriesPerRequest to null**: BullMQ requires this ioredis option or connections fail.

## Summary

BullMQ provides robust background job processing for Node.js via Redis. Producers add jobs to queues, workers process them asynchronously with retry logic, rate limiting, and priority ordering. Use job flows for complex multi-step workflows, QueueEvents for monitoring, and Bull Board for visual management. Always run workers as separate processes from your API server.

problems.code:
await queue.add('job', data, {
  removeOnComplete: { age: 3600, count: 1000 },
  removeOnFail: { age: 86400, count: 5000 },
});

8.3.2.body:
# RabbitMQ: Exchanges, Queues, and Routing

## Introduction

RabbitMQ is a message broker that implements the Advanced Message Queuing Protocol (AMQP). Unlike BullMQ which is Redis-based and focused on job queues, RabbitMQ is a full-featured message broker with sophisticated routing, multiple exchange types, and guaranteed delivery. It excels in scenarios where messages need to be routed to different consumers based on content or patterns.

## RabbitMQ vs BullMQ

```
┌───────────────────┬───────────────────┬───────────────────┐
│                   │ BullMQ            │ RabbitMQ          │
├───────────────────┼───────────────────┼───────────────────┤
│ Backing store     │ Redis             │ Erlang/OTP        │
│ Protocol          │ Custom (Redis)    │ AMQP 0-9-1        │
│ Use case          │ Job queues        │ Message routing   │
│ Routing           │ Queue name only   │ Exchanges+routing │
│ Priority queues   │ Yes               │ Yes               │
│ Delayed messages  │ Built-in          │ Plugin required   │
│ Clustering        │ Via Redis Cluster │ Built-in          │
│ Message ordering  │ FIFO per queue    │ FIFO per queue    │
│ Persistence       │ Via Redis         │ Built-in          │
└───────────────────┴───────────────────┴───────────────────┘
```

## Core Concepts

```
Producer ──> Exchange ──> Binding ──> Queue ──> Consumer

┌──────────┐     ┌──────────────┐     ┌───────────┐     ┌──────────┐
│ Producer │────>│   Exchange   │────>│   Queue   │────>│ Consumer │
│          │     │ (routes msgs)│     │ (buffers) │     │          │
└──────────┘     └──────────────┘     └───────────┘     └──────────┘
                       │
                   Routing rules
                   (bindings + routing keys)
```

## Setup with amqplib

```javascript
import amqp from 'amqplib';

async function connect() {
  const connection = await amqp.connect(process.env.RABBITMQ_URL || 'amqp://localhost');
  const channel = await connection.createChannel();

  // Handle connection errors
  connection.on('error', (err) => {
    console.error('RabbitMQ connection error:', err);
  });
  connection.on('close', () => {
    console.log('RabbitMQ connection closed. Reconnecting...');
    setTimeout(connect, 5000);
  });

  return { connection, channel };
}
```

## Exchange Types

### 1. Direct Exchange

Routes messages to queues with an exact matching routing key.

```
Producer                  Direct Exchange              Queues
  │                            │
  │ routingKey="error"   ──────┼──> [error queue]    ──> Error handler
  │ routingKey="info"    ──────┼──> [info queue]     ──> Log aggregator
  │ routingKey="warning" ──────┼──> [warning queue]  ──> Alert service
```

```javascript
async function setupDirectExchange(channel) {
  const exchange = 'logs.direct';

  await channel.assertExchange(exchange, 'direct', { durable: true });

  // Create queues and bind with routing keys
  const errorQueue = await channel.assertQueue('logs.error', { durable: true });
  const infoQueue = await channel.assertQueue('logs.info', { durable: true });

  await channel.bindQueue(errorQueue.queue, exchange, 'error');
  await channel.bindQueue(infoQueue.queue, exchange, 'info');

  // Publish
  channel.publish(exchange, 'error', Buffer.from(JSON.stringify({
    message: 'Database connection failed',
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
  })), { persistent: true });

  // Consume
  channel.consume(errorQueue.queue, (msg) => {
    const log = JSON.parse(msg.content.toString());
    console.error('ERROR:', log.message);
    channel.ack(msg); // Acknowledge processing
  });
}
```

### 2. Fanout Exchange

Broadcasts messages to ALL bound queues (like pub/sub).

```
Producer ──> Fanout Exchange ──┬──> Queue A (Email service)
                               ├──> Queue B (SMS service)
                               └──> Queue C (Push notification)
```

```javascript
async function setupFanoutExchange(channel) {
  const exchange = 'notifications.fanout';
  await channel.assertExchange(exchange, 'fanout', { durable: true });

  // Each service gets its own queue
  const emailQ = await channel.assertQueue('notifications.email', { durable: true });
  const smsQ = await channel.assertQueue('notifications.sms', { durable: true });
  const pushQ = await channel.assertQueue('notifications.push', { durable: true });

  // Bind all queues (routing key ignored for fanout)
  await channel.bindQueue(emailQ.queue, exchange, '');
  await channel.bindQueue(smsQ.queue, exchange, '');
  await channel.bindQueue(pushQ.queue, exchange, '');

  // One publish reaches all three queues
  channel.publish(exchange, '', Buffer.from(JSON.stringify({
    userId: 'user-123',
    event: 'order_completed',
    orderId: 'ORD-456',
  })), { persistent: true });
}
```

### 3. Topic Exchange

Routes based on pattern matching with wildcards.

```
Routing key format: <facility>.<severity>.<region>

  order.created.us    ──> Matches: order.* , order.created.* , *.*.us
  order.cancelled.eu  ──> Matches: order.* , *.cancelled.*
  payment.failed.us   ──> Matches: payment.* , *.failed.* , #.us

  * = exactly one word
  # = zero or more words
```

```javascript
async function setupTopicExchange(channel) {
  const exchange = 'events.topic';
  await channel.assertExchange(exchange, 'topic', { durable: true });

  // Order processing service - all order events
  const orderQ = await channel.assertQueue('events.orders', { durable: true });
  await channel.bindQueue(orderQ.queue, exchange, 'order.*');

  // Payment alerts - only failures
  const paymentAlertQ = await channel.assertQueue('events.payment-alerts', { durable: true });
  await channel.bindQueue(paymentAlertQ.queue, exchange, 'payment.failed');

  // US region monitor - everything from US
  const usQ = await channel.assertQueue('events.us-region', { durable: true });
  await channel.bindQueue(usQ.queue, exchange, '*.*.us');

  // Audit log - capture everything
  const auditQ = await channel.assertQueue('events.audit', { durable: true });
  await channel.bindQueue(auditQ.queue, exchange, '#');

  // Publish events
  channel.publish(exchange, 'order.created.us', Buffer.from(JSON.stringify({
    orderId: 'ORD-123',
    region: 'us',
  })));
  // This goes to: orderQ, usQ, auditQ
}
```

## Message Acknowledgment

```javascript
// Manual acknowledgment (recommended for reliability)
channel.consume('tasks', async (msg) => {
  try {
    const task = JSON.parse(msg.content.toString());
    await processTask(task);
    channel.ack(msg);          // Success - remove from queue
  } catch (err) {
    if (err.retryable) {
      channel.nack(msg, false, true);  // Requeue for retry
    } else {
      channel.nack(msg, false, false); // Don't requeue (goes to DLQ if configured)
    }
  }
}, { noAck: false }); // Manual ack mode

// Prefetch: limit unacknowledged messages per consumer
channel.prefetch(10); // Only deliver 10 unacked messages at a time
```

## Dead Letter Queues

```javascript
async function setupWithDLQ(channel) {
  // Dead letter exchange and queue
  await channel.assertExchange('dlx', 'direct', { durable: true });
  await channel.assertQueue('dead-letters', { durable: true });
  await channel.bindQueue('dead-letters', 'dlx', 'failed');

  // Main queue with DLQ configuration
  await channel.assertQueue('tasks', {
    durable: true,
    arguments: {
      'x-dead-letter-exchange': 'dlx',
      'x-dead-letter-routing-key': 'failed',
      'x-message-ttl': 300000,    // Messages expire after 5 min
      'x-max-length': 10000,       // Max queue size
    },
  });

  // Failed messages automatically go to dead-letters queue
  // Process dead letters for investigation
  channel.consume('dead-letters', (msg) => {
    const original = JSON.parse(msg.content.toString());
    const reason = msg.properties.headers['x-death']?.[0]?.reason;
    console.error(`Dead letter (reason: ${reason}):`, original);
    // Log to monitoring system, alert ops
    channel.ack(msg);
  });
}
```

## RabbitMQ with NestJS Microservices

```javascript
// main.ts - Microservice setup
import { NestFactory } from '@nestjs/core';
import { MicroserviceOptions, Transport } from '@nestjs/microservices';

const app = await NestFactory.createMicroservice(AppModule, {
  transport: Transport.RMQ,
  options: {
    urls: ['amqp://localhost:5672'],
    queue: 'orders_queue',
    queueOptions: { durable: true },
    prefetchCount: 10,
  },
});

await app.listen();

// order.controller.ts
import { Controller } from '@nestjs/common';
import { MessagePattern, Payload, Ctx, RmqContext } from '@nestjs/microservices';

@Controller()
export class OrderController {
  @MessagePattern('order_created')
  async handleOrderCreated(@Payload() data: any, @Ctx() context: RmqContext) {
    const channel = context.getChannelRef();
    const originalMsg = context.getMessage();

    try {
      await this.orderService.processOrder(data);
      channel.ack(originalMsg);
    } catch (err) {
      channel.nack(originalMsg, false, true); // Requeue
    }
  }
}
```

## Connection Management

```javascript
class RabbitMQConnection {
  constructor(url) {
    this.url = url;
    this.connection = null;
    this.channel = null;
  }

  async connect() {
    this.connection = await amqp.connect(this.url);
    this.channel = await this.connection.createConfirmChannel();

    // Publish confirmations
    this.channel.on('return', (msg) => {
      console.error('Message returned (unroutable):', msg);
    });

    this.connection.on('close', () => {
      console.log('Connection closed. Reconnecting...');
      setTimeout(() => this.connect(), 5000);
    });

    return this;
  }

  async publishWithConfirm(exchange, routingKey, data) {
    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
      this.channel.publish(
        exchange,
        routingKey,
        Buffer.from(JSON.stringify(data)),
        { persistent: true, mandatory: true },
        (err) => {
          if (err) reject(err);
          else resolve();
        }
      );
    });
  }

  async close() {
    await this.channel?.close();
    await this.connection?.close();
  }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Not acknowledging messages**: Unacknowledged messages stay in the queue and are redelivered when the consumer disconnects, causing duplicates.
2. **Using one channel for everything**: Channels are not thread-safe. Use one channel per consumer/producer thread.
3. **Not setting prefetch**: Without prefetch, RabbitMQ dumps all messages to one consumer, leaving others idle.
4. **Losing messages without persistent flag**: Messages are stored in memory by default. Use `{ persistent: true }` for durability.

## Summary

RabbitMQ provides sophisticated message routing through exchanges (direct, fanout, topic) and queues. It excels at routing messages to different services based on content, unlike BullMQ which is focused on job processing. Use direct exchanges for targeted routing, fanout for broadcasting, and topic for pattern-based routing. Always use manual acknowledgment, configure dead letter queues, and set prefetch counts for reliable message processing.

8.3.3.body:
# Dead Letter Queues, Retry Strategies, and Idempotency

## Introduction

In distributed systems, failures are not exceptional — they are expected. Messages will fail to process due to temporary errors (network timeouts, service outages) and permanent errors (invalid data, business logic violations). Dead letter queues, retry strategies, and idempotent processing form the triad of reliable message handling.

## Dead Letter Queues (DLQ)

A dead letter queue captures messages that cannot be processed successfully, preventing them from being lost or retried infinitely.

```
Normal Flow:
Queue ──> Consumer ──> Process ──> ACK (removed from queue)

Failure Flow:
Queue ──> Consumer ──> Process ──> FAIL
                                     │
                                     ├── Retry (requeue)
                                     │     └── Eventually succeeds or...
                                     │
                                     └── Dead Letter Queue (after max retries)
                                           └── Manual investigation
                                           └── Automated alerting
```

### DLQ with BullMQ

BullMQ doesn't have a separate DLQ — failed jobs stay in the failed state. But you can implement DLQ-like behavior:

```javascript
import { Queue, Worker } from 'bullmq';

const mainQueue = new Queue('orders', { connection });
const dlq = new Queue('orders-dlq', { connection });

const worker = new Worker('orders', async (job) => {
  try {
    await processOrder(job.data);
  } catch (err) {
    // Check if this is the final attempt
    if (job.attemptsMade >= job.opts.attempts - 1) {
      // Move to DLQ with error context
      await dlq.add('failed-order', {
        originalJob: {
          id: job.id,
          name: job.name,
          data: job.data,
          attemptsMade: job.attemptsMade,
        },
        error: {
          message: err.message,
          stack: err.stack,
        },
        failedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
      });
    }
    throw err; // Re-throw so BullMQ handles retry
  }
}, {
  connection,
  attempts: 3,
  backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 1000 },
});

// DLQ processor - alert or attempt remediation
const dlqWorker = new Worker('orders-dlq', async (job) => {
  const { originalJob, error } = job.data;
  console.error(`DLQ: Order ${originalJob.data.orderId} failed: ${error.message}`);

  // Send alert
  await alertOps({
    type: 'dead_letter',
    queue: 'orders',
    jobId: originalJob.id,
    error: error.message,
  });

  // Optionally: attempt automated remediation
  if (error.message.includes('inventory')) {
    await mainQueue.add('orders', originalJob.data, {
      delay: 300000, // Retry in 5 minutes
      attempts: 1,
    });
  }
}, { connection });
```

## Retry Strategies

### 1. Fixed Delay

```javascript
// Retry every 5 seconds
await queue.add('job', data, {
  attempts: 5,
  backoff: { type: 'fixed', delay: 5000 },
});
// Retries at: 5s, 5s, 5s, 5s
```

### 2. Exponential Backoff

```javascript
// Exponentially increasing delays
await queue.add('job', data, {
  attempts: 5,
  backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 1000 },
});
// Retries at: 1s, 2s, 4s, 8s
```

### 3. Custom Backoff with Jitter

```javascript
// Custom backoff strategy
await queue.add('api-call', data, {
  attempts: 5,
  backoff: { type: 'custom' },
});

// In worker
const worker = new Worker('api-call', processor, {
  connection,
  settings: {
    backoffStrategy: (attemptsMade) => {
      // Exponential backoff with full jitter
      const baseDelay = 1000;
      const maxDelay = 30000;
      const exponential = Math.min(baseDelay * Math.pow(2, attemptsMade), maxDelay);
      const jitter = Math.random() * exponential;
      return Math.floor(jitter);
    },
  },
});
```

### 4. Circuit Breaker Pattern with Retry

```javascript
class CircuitBreaker {
  constructor({ failureThreshold = 5, resetTimeout = 30000 } = {}) {
    this.failureCount = 0;
    this.failureThreshold = failureThreshold;
    this.resetTimeout = resetTimeout;
    this.state = 'CLOSED'; // CLOSED, OPEN, HALF_OPEN
    this.nextAttempt = null;
  }

  async execute(fn) {
    if (this.state === 'OPEN') {
      if (Date.now() < this.nextAttempt) {
        throw new Error('Circuit breaker is OPEN');
      }
      this.state = 'HALF_OPEN';
    }

    try {
      const result = await fn();
      this.onSuccess();
      return result;
    } catch (err) {
      this.onFailure();
      throw err;
    }
  }

  onSuccess() {
    this.failureCount = 0;
    this.state = 'CLOSED';
  }

  onFailure() {
    this.failureCount++;
    if (this.failureCount >= this.failureThreshold) {
      this.state = 'OPEN';
      this.nextAttempt = Date.now() + this.resetTimeout;
    }
  }
}

// Use in worker
const paymentBreaker = new CircuitBreaker({ failureThreshold: 3 });

const worker = new Worker('payments', async (job) => {
  return paymentBreaker.execute(async () => {
    return await paymentGateway.charge(job.data);
  });
}, { connection, attempts: 5, backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 2000 } });
```

## Classifying Errors: Retryable vs Permanent

Not all errors should be retried:

```javascript
class RetryableError extends Error {
  constructor(message) {
    super(message);
    this.retryable = true;
  }
}

class PermanentError extends Error {
  constructor(message) {
    super(message);
    this.retryable = false;
  }
}

const worker = new Worker('orders', async (job) => {
  try {
    const result = await processOrder(job.data);
    return result;
  } catch (err) {
    // Classify the error
    if (err.code === 'ECONNRESET' || err.code === 'ETIMEDOUT') {
      throw new RetryableError(`Network error: ${err.message}`);
    }
    if (err.status === 400 || err.status === 422) {
      // Bad data - retrying won't help
      throw new PermanentError(`Invalid data: ${err.message}`);
    }
    if (err.status === 429) {
      throw new RetryableError('Rate limited');
    }
    if (err.status >= 500) {
      throw new RetryableError(`Server error: ${err.message}`);
    }
    throw err;
  }
}, {
  connection,
  attempts: 5,
  backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 1000 },
});

// Skip retries for permanent errors
worker.on('failed', async (job, err) => {
  if (!err.retryable && job.attemptsMade < job.opts.attempts) {
    // Move directly to DLQ instead of retrying
    await job.moveToFailed(err, job.token, true); // true = don't retry
  }
});
```

## Idempotency

An operation is **idempotent** if performing it multiple times has the same effect as performing it once. This is critical because retries WILL cause duplicate processing.

```
Without Idempotency:
  Process payment: charge $100
  Retry (duplicate): charge $100 again
  Result: customer charged $200 ← BUG!

With Idempotency:
  Process payment: charge $100 (idempotency key: "pay-ORD123")
  Retry (duplicate): check key "pay-ORD123" already processed
  Result: customer charged $100 ← CORRECT
```

### Idempotency Key Pattern

```javascript
class IdempotentProcessor {
  constructor(redis) {
    this.redis = redis;
  }

  async processOnce(idempotencyKey, ttl, processFn) {
    // Try to acquire the idempotency lock
    const acquired = await this.redis.set(
      `idempotent:${idempotencyKey}`,
      'processing',
      'NX',    // Only set if not exists
      'EX',    // Expire
      ttl      // TTL in seconds
    );

    if (!acquired) {
      // Already processed or processing
      const result = await this.redis.get(`idempotent:${idempotencyKey}:result`);
      if (result) return JSON.parse(result);
      throw new Error('Duplicate processing detected');
    }

    try {
      const result = await processFn();

      // Store the result for duplicate requests
      await this.redis.setex(
        `idempotent:${idempotencyKey}:result`,
        ttl,
        JSON.stringify(result)
      );
      await this.redis.set(`idempotent:${idempotencyKey}`, 'completed', 'EX', ttl);

      return result;
    } catch (err) {
      // Remove lock so it can be retried
      await this.redis.del(`idempotent:${idempotencyKey}`);
      throw err;
    }
  }
}

// Usage in worker
const idempotent = new IdempotentProcessor(redis);

const worker = new Worker('payments', async (job) => {
  const idempotencyKey = `payment:${job.data.orderId}`;

  return idempotent.processOnce(idempotencyKey, 86400, async () => {
    const charge = await stripe.charges.create({
      amount: job.data.amount,
      currency: 'usd',
      customer: job.data.customerId,
      idempotency_key: idempotencyKey, // Stripe also supports idempotency
    });
    return { chargeId: charge.id, amount: charge.amount };
  });
}, { connection, attempts: 3, backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 2000 } });
```

### Database-Level Idempotency

```javascript
async function processOrderIdempotent(orderId, action) {
  // Use a processed_events table
  return prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
    // Check if already processed
    const existing = await tx.processedEvent.findUnique({
      where: { eventKey: `order:${orderId}:${action}` },
    });

    if (existing) {
      console.log(`Already processed: order:${orderId}:${action}`);
      return existing.result;
    }

    // Process the action
    const result = await performAction(tx, orderId, action);

    // Record that we processed it
    await tx.processedEvent.create({
      data: {
        eventKey: `order:${orderId}:${action}`,
        result: JSON.stringify(result),
        processedAt: new Date(),
      },
    });

    return result;
  });
}
```

## Combining All Three Patterns

```javascript
// Complete reliable message processing setup

const mainQueue = new Queue('order-processing', { connection });
const dlq = new Queue('order-processing-dlq', { connection });
const idempotent = new IdempotentProcessor(redis);

const worker = new Worker('order-processing', async (job) => {
  const { orderId, action, timestamp } = job.data;
  const idempotencyKey = `${orderId}:${action}:${timestamp}`;

  // 1. Idempotency check
  return idempotent.processOnce(idempotencyKey, 86400, async () => {
    // 2. Classify and process
    try {
      switch (action) {
        case 'charge':
          return await chargeOrder(orderId);
        case 'ship':
          return await shipOrder(orderId);
        case 'notify':
          return await notifyCustomer(orderId);
        default:
          throw new PermanentError(`Unknown action: ${action}`);
      }
    } catch (err) {
      // 3. Error classification
      if (err instanceof PermanentError) {
        // Move to DLQ immediately
        await dlq.add('permanent-failure', {
          originalJob: job.data,
          error: err.message,
          failedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
        });
        return { status: 'permanent_failure', error: err.message };
      }
      throw err; // Retryable errors bubble up for retry
    }
  });
}, {
  connection,
  concurrency: 10,
  attempts: 5,
  backoff: { type: 'exponential', delay: 2000 },
});
```

## Common Pitfalls

1. **Retrying permanent errors**: Classifying all errors as retryable wastes resources and delays DLQ processing. Always distinguish retryable from permanent errors.
2. **No idempotency on payment processing**: Double-charging customers is a severe bug. Every payment operation must be idempotent.
3. **Infinite retry loops**: Without max attempts, a poisoned message retries forever. Always set a maximum.
4. **DLQ without monitoring**: Messages sitting in the DLQ unnoticed means lost business. Alert on DLQ depth.

## Summary

Dead letter queues capture permanently failed messages for investigation. Retry strategies with exponential backoff and jitter handle transient failures gracefully. Idempotency ensures that retried messages produce the same result as the first processing. Together, these three patterns make your message processing reliable in the face of inevitable distributed system failures.

